was tension
in the house, and I felt
completely out of

25:15.981 --> 25:20.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
control on what to do, what kind
of limits
to set, how this was affecting
them.

25:21.053 --> 25:23.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Now that you
have done all
this research, what was it, I'm
curious, that

25:24.089 --> 25:25.924 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
most surprised you that you
found?

25:26.024 --> 25:28.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. DELANEY RUSTON: Well, I
think one thing
that really helped me to start
to be a better

25:28.894 --> 25:35.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
parent around this is to learn
that the dopamine
that's secreted in the brain's
pleasure center

25:35.901 --> 25:42.307 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
when we get new bits of
information and we
look at the screens, that center
of the brain

25:42.408 --> 25:45.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is most activated when we're
kids and we're
teenagers.

25:46.044 --> 25:53.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, knowing that they are so
pulled into these
in a way that we can't even
understand has

25:53.485 --> 25:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made me not be as angry at them,
but realize
there's a lot more I need to do
as -- in my

25:59.958 --> 26:01.860 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
parenting.

26:01.960 --> 26:03.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, these are
little electronic
drug delivery devices? I know
that's a crude

26:04.029 --> 26:05.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
