29:54.660 --> 29:58.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's not going to get kids to
open up and
feel comfortable to be a part of
this, and

29:58.697 --> 30:00.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's really what this is going
to take.

30:00.465 --> 30:11.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: For the "PBS
NewsHour,"
I'm William Brangham in
Washington, D.C.

30:11.343 --> 30:21.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: For the better
part of two
decades, there's been a growing
recognition

30:22.054 --> 30:25.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that medical errors kill too
many patients
in the U.S.

30:25.857 --> 30:31.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While exact numbers are elusive,
a new analysis
and estimate portrays an even
grimmer picture.

30:31.530 --> 30:38.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The new paper finds that as many
as 250,000
people die each year from errors
in hospitals

30:38.537 --> 30:43.508 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and other health care
facilities. That would
make it the third leading cause
of death in

30:43.608 --> 30:47.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the U.S., ahead of respiratory
disease, accidents
and even stroke.

30:47.512 --> 30:50.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dr. Martin Makary, a professor
of surgery
at the Johns Hopkins University
School of

30:51.049 --> 30:53.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Medicine who led the research,
joins me now.

30:53.185 --> 30:55.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, how did we get to this
number? What did
your research find?

30:55.854 --> 30:57.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. MARTIN MAKARY, Professor of
Surgery, Johns
Hopkins University School of
Medicine: Well,

30:57.723 --> 31:01.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we took the best available
studies, the data
from the medical literature, and
we basically

31:01.927 --> 31:07.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
came up with a meta-analysis
point estimate,
and then asked, where would that
fall if medical

31:07.566 --> 31:09.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
error were counted as a disease?

31:09.568 --> 31:14.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It turns out that we learned
that the CDC
doesn't consider medical error
to be a cause

31:15.006 --> 31:20.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of death in listing our national
health statistics
each year, even though the point
estimate

31:20.345 --> 31:24.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
comes right in between number
two and number
three on the list, which means
medical error

31:24.616 --> 31:28.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is the number three cause of
death in the
United States. We're just not
measuring it.

31:28.386 --> 31:30.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: OK. So, let's
talk a little
bit about the methodology.

31:30.655 --> 31:36.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the numbers are scarce, are
these studies
representative enough sample
sets to be able

31:36.428 --> 31:38.263 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to extrapolate this
quarter-million?

31:38.363 --> 31:42.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. MARTIN MAKARY: These are
studies of hundreds
of thousands of hospitalizations
in the top

31:42.667 --> 31:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
medical journals. And they are
updating the
1999 Institute of Medicine
report.

31:48.707 --> 31:53.678 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's broad consensus that
the range
is somewhere between 200,000 and
400,000.

31:53.779 --> 31:59.284 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Our analysis came up with
251,000. No matter
what number you pick, it is well
above the

31:59.384 --> 32:04.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
currently listed number three
cause of death.
And it turns out that the reason
it's not

32:04.322 --> 32:10.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being counted is that the system
relies on
billing codes to compile our
national health

32:10.328 --> 32:12.197 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
statistics.

32:12.297 --> 32:17.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But people don't always die of a
